{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613144","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613144"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:31:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:31:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16307"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16307"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8998"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72925"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8998"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"496"},{"type":"tags","id":"659"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7482"},{"type":"tags","id":"9718"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21419"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21423"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72925"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EOtitis externa and otitis media are common ear infections that present with different clinical features.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most characteristic of otitis externa compared to otitis media?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pain on manipulation of the pinna and tragus","Bulging tympanic membrane","Conductive hearing loss","Peak incidence in children under five years","Clear appearance of ear canal"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPain on manipulation of the pinna and tragus\u003C/strong\u003E is a hallmark sign of otitis externa, distinguishing it from otitis media. Inflammation of the external ear canal makes movement of the cartilaginous structures particularly painful.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options are more characteristic of otitis media:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebulging tympanic membrane\u003C/strong\u003E is typical of acute otitis media due to middle ear fluid accumulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConductive hearing loss\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with otitis media due to middle ear effusion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeak incidence in children under five years\u003C/strong\u003E describes otitis media, while otitis externa can affect any age group\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eclear appearance of ear canal\u003C/strong\u003E is not seen in otitis externa, which typically shows erythema and edema of the canal\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOtitis externa is often associated with swimming (\u0027swimmer\u0027s ear\u0027) or local trauma that disrupts the protective cerumen barrier, allowing bacterial colonisation of the external ear canal.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Otitis externa is an infection of the external ear canal characterised by pain on manipulation of the pinna and tragus.","Swimming and local trauma are key risk factors for otitis externa due to disruption of the protective cerumen barrier.","Otitis externa presents with ear canal erythema and oedema, while otitis media primarily affects the middle ear."],"references":["Wiegand S, Berner R, Schneider A, Lundershausen E, Dietz A. Otitis Externa. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2019 Mar 29;116(13):224-234. doi: 10.3238/arztebl.2019.0224. PMID: 31064650; PMCID: PMC6522672.","Hajioff D, MacKeith S. Otitis externa. BMJ Clin Evid. 2015 Jun 15;2015:0510. PMID: 26074134; PMCID: PMC4466798.","Jackson EA, Geer K. Acute Otitis Externa: Rapid Evidence Review. Am Fam Physician. 2023 Feb;107(2):145-151. PMID: 36791445."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16307"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T18:21:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T21:15:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8998"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72925"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"p